1
00:00:00,877 --> 00:00:02,337
(HARVEY READING)

2
00:00:02,420 --> 00:00:04,381
(ON PHONE) <i>Rachel,
it's Professor Dunbar.</i>

3
00:00:04,464 --> 00:00:06,841
I was wondering if you'd be
interested in helping me

4
00:00:06,925 --> 00:00:08,176
<i>with the Innocence Project.</i>

5
00:00:08,259 --> 00:00:10,428
You want me to help you get
an innocent man off death row?

6
00:00:10,512 --> 00:00:12,639
What do you want,
Harvey?
Help me protect Mike Ross.

7
00:00:12,722 --> 00:00:15,016
He's in there
with a guy I put away
and the guy is no joke.

8
00:00:15,100 --> 00:00:16,184
What am I supposed to do?

9
00:00:16,267 --> 00:00:18,269
You're supposed to move
the guy to another prison.

10
00:00:18,353 --> 00:00:20,021
You want me one-on-one,
you got it.

11
00:00:20,105 --> 00:00:22,148
I'm gonna use this
and they're gonna hold you.

12
00:00:22,232 --> 00:00:23,483
No!
What's going on here?

13
00:00:24,901 --> 00:00:26,319
Why did you come back
with the guard?

14
00:00:26,403 --> 00:00:28,029
I didn't do it to
get you to forgive me.

15
00:00:28,113 --> 00:00:30,031
I never should have let him
in here in the first place.

16
00:00:30,115 --> 00:00:31,825
The time you served
while awaiting trial

17
00:00:31,908 --> 00:00:33,535
was never factored
into your sentence.

18
00:00:33,618 --> 00:00:35,537
You're eligible for parole
in six weeks.

19
00:00:35,620 --> 00:00:37,622
You think I don't
know this is your
protector's idea

20
00:00:37,706 --> 00:00:38,790
to get me off your back?

21
00:00:38,873 --> 00:00:39,874
No, Frank.

22
00:00:39,958 --> 00:00:42,460
Harvey's idea
was for me to
tell these guys

23
00:00:42,544 --> 00:00:43,712
that you were an informant.

24
00:00:43,795 --> 00:00:45,547
I figured out a way
to get Mike out early.

25
00:00:45,630 --> 00:00:46,673
What's the catch?

26
00:00:46,756 --> 00:00:47,882
He has to inform
on his roommate.

27
00:00:47,966 --> 00:00:49,384
Mike gets him to turn,
he's free.

28
00:00:49,467 --> 00:00:50,760
When do you need
an answer by?

29
00:00:50,844 --> 00:00:51,886
Yesterday.

30
00:00:51,970 --> 00:00:53,304
And the answer
needs to be yes.

31
00:00:56,182 --> 00:00:57,225
JESSICA:
Harvey, wait a second.

32
00:00:57,308 --> 00:00:59,394
Where are you going?
Where do you think I'm going?

33
00:00:59,477 --> 00:01:00,478
I'm going to see Mike.

34
00:01:00,562 --> 00:01:01,563
And I know
what you're going to say,

35
00:01:01,646 --> 00:01:03,898
but Mike went to prison
so we wouldn't have to,

36
00:01:03,982 --> 00:01:06,234
and now he's in danger
from a guy I put away.

37
00:01:06,317 --> 00:01:08,111
So, you'll forgive me
if I don't stand around

38
00:01:08,194 --> 00:01:09,904
and wait for you
to drop the hammer.

39
00:01:09,988 --> 00:01:11,156
You think I like
the idea of him

40
00:01:11,239 --> 00:01:12,449
rotting in that place?

41
00:01:12,532 --> 00:01:14,033
But if you want
this thing to work,

42
00:01:14,117 --> 00:01:15,827
you can't go running up there
in the middle of the night.

43
00:01:15,910 --> 00:01:18,121
You heard Cahill,
he needs an answer yesterday.

44
00:01:18,204 --> 00:01:20,123
What he needs is results.

45
00:01:20,206 --> 00:01:21,916
And if Mike's lawyer
pulls him out of his cell

46
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:23,042
in the middle of the night,

47
00:01:23,126 --> 00:01:25,128
then his roommate is going to
sense there's something wrong

48
00:01:25,211 --> 00:01:27,005
before this thing
even gets started.

49
00:01:28,214 --> 00:01:31,050
Fine. But I'm going up there
first thing in the morning,

50
00:01:31,134 --> 00:01:33,178
and nothing you say
is going to stop me.

51
00:01:41,561 --> 00:01:42,771
KEVIN: Can't sleep?

52
00:01:43,229 --> 00:01:44,355
Not really.

53
00:01:44,522 --> 00:01:45,982
Well, as long
as you're up,

54
00:01:46,065 --> 00:01:47,317
you might want to think
about putting up

55
00:01:47,400 --> 00:01:48,818
some pictures of your own.

56
00:01:49,027 --> 00:01:51,488
That way you won't
have to keep staring at mine.

57
00:01:56,034 --> 00:01:57,368
How old are they?

58
00:01:59,204 --> 00:02:03,166
Maddy is seven
and Nate just turned five.

59
00:02:04,709 --> 00:02:06,044
They look really sweet.

60
00:02:06,711 --> 00:02:07,879
Yeah, they're...

61
00:02:08,713 --> 00:02:09,839
They're great.

62
00:02:10,215 --> 00:02:11,466
How often
do you get to see them?

63
00:02:11,549 --> 00:02:12,550
I don't.

64
00:02:12,634 --> 00:02:13,635
What do you mean
you don't?

65
00:02:13,718 --> 00:02:16,221
Bad divorce or something?
Nah, nah. Nothing like that.

66
00:02:16,930 --> 00:02:18,139
We've been married
for 10 years.

67
00:02:18,223 --> 00:02:19,724
I just... I just
don't let them come here.

68
00:02:19,808 --> 00:02:20,850
What? Why not?

69
00:02:20,934 --> 00:02:22,685
They shouldn't see
their father as a criminal.

70
00:02:22,769 --> 00:02:24,979
Kevin. Come on, man.
I know it's hard on them.

71
00:02:25,063 --> 00:02:26,940
It tears me up every
single day that I'm here.

72
00:02:27,023 --> 00:02:29,526
But they're kids.
They're resilient.

73
00:02:30,527 --> 00:02:31,903
Yeah, I wouldn't be so sure.

74
00:02:31,986 --> 00:02:33,238
Well, Mike,
you don't have kids.

75
00:02:33,321 --> 00:02:34,531
So, you don't know.

76
00:02:34,614 --> 00:02:35,698
No, I don't.

77
00:02:35,782 --> 00:02:38,493
But I do know what it's like
to be a kid missing his dad.

78
00:02:38,576 --> 00:02:40,578
Please don't tell me your
old man abandoned the family.

79
00:02:41,746 --> 00:02:45,917
Both my parents died
in a car accident
when I was 11.

80
00:02:46,626 --> 00:02:48,253
Hit by a drunk driver.

81
00:02:48,753 --> 00:02:50,171
Jesus. That's...

82
00:02:50,505 --> 00:02:51,756
I'm sorry, Mike.

83
00:02:53,591 --> 00:02:55,426
Well, it was a long time ago.

84
00:02:56,970 --> 00:02:58,179
Kevin, I understand
the instinct

85
00:02:58,263 --> 00:02:59,264
to protect your children,

86
00:02:59,347 --> 00:03:01,349
but what are you
protecting them from?

87
00:03:01,432 --> 00:03:02,475
What do you mean?

88
00:03:02,559 --> 00:03:04,269
I mean, we've been roommates
for a while now.

89
00:03:04,352 --> 00:03:05,436
Don't you think it's time
you told me

90
00:03:05,520 --> 00:03:06,813
what you're in here for?

91
00:03:07,647 --> 00:03:08,648
(DOOR BUZZING)

92
00:03:09,065 --> 00:03:10,149
GUARD: Hey, Ross.

93
00:03:10,441 --> 00:03:11,860
Your lawyer's here.
Now?

94
00:03:11,943 --> 00:03:12,986
I'm just the messenger.

95
00:03:13,069 --> 00:03:14,279
You want out
of this box or not?

96
00:03:35,633 --> 00:03:37,427
Mr. Bailey,
my name is Rachel Zane.

97
00:03:37,510 --> 00:03:39,053
<i>I am a law student
at Columbia,</i>

98
00:03:39,137 --> 00:03:40,889
<i>and I'm here to talk to you
about your case.</i>

99
00:03:40,972 --> 00:03:42,015
<i>Student?</i>
Yes.

100
00:03:42,098 --> 00:03:43,808
We work alongside
the Innocence Project

101
00:03:43,892 --> 00:03:46,060
<i>to determine if you have
the criteria for an appeal.</i>

102
00:03:46,269 --> 00:03:48,897
<i>Do you know how long
I been sitting on death row?</i>

103
00:03:48,980 --> 00:03:50,732
Twelve years.
I read your file.

104
00:03:51,107 --> 00:03:53,401
And for the last 10 of them
I've been writing letters

105
00:03:53,484 --> 00:03:56,821
<i>and begging any lawyer
to listen to my story.</i>

106
00:03:57,238 --> 00:03:59,991
And they finally get around
to getting back to me,

107
00:04:00,491 --> 00:04:02,452
<i>and they don't
even have the courtesy</i>

108
00:04:02,535 --> 00:04:04,245
<i>of sending me a real lawyer?</i>

109
00:04:04,329 --> 00:04:07,498
<i>Mr. Bailey, trust me,
I will fight for you.</i>

110
00:04:07,665 --> 00:04:08,833
You're a student.

111
00:04:09,834 --> 00:04:11,461
<i>You can't do shit for me.</i>

112
00:04:13,171 --> 00:04:14,213
<i>Well, you know what?</i>

113
00:04:14,297 --> 00:04:16,591
You killed two people
in cold blood.

114
00:04:18,051 --> 00:04:19,302
<i>You know it and I know it,</i>

115
00:04:19,385 --> 00:04:20,511
<i>and that's why
you're in there.</i>

116
00:04:20,595 --> 00:04:22,221
<i>So, thank you
for making the decision</i>

117
00:04:22,305 --> 00:04:24,974
<i>to not take your case
an easy one.</i>

118
00:04:25,391 --> 00:04:26,643
You don't know me.

119
00:04:26,726 --> 00:04:28,102
<i>All you know
is what you've read</i>

120
00:04:28,186 --> 00:04:29,896
<i>in some damn file.</i>

121
00:04:30,688 --> 00:04:32,231
<i>I didn't kill anyone.</i>

122
00:04:32,815 --> 00:04:34,567
<i>I've been saying it
for 12 years</i>

123
00:04:34,651 --> 00:04:35,777
<i>and I can prove it.</i>

124
00:04:35,860 --> 00:04:37,737
You're right.
I don't know you.

125
00:04:37,862 --> 00:04:39,447
<i>And you don't
know me either.</i>

126
00:04:40,448 --> 00:04:41,532
<i>So, do you want
to take a chance</i>

127
00:04:41,616 --> 00:04:42,992
<i>on each other or not?</i>

128
00:04:44,702 --> 00:04:46,037
<i>I need help...</i>

129
00:04:47,872 --> 00:04:49,040
<i>Ms. Zane.</i>

130
00:04:51,209 --> 00:04:52,794
<i>So, let me help you.</i>

131
00:04:57,924 --> 00:04:59,008
Harvey, what are you
doing here?

132
00:04:59,092 --> 00:05:00,635
There's something
I need to talk to you about.

133
00:05:00,718 --> 00:05:01,761
Sit down.

134
00:05:01,844 --> 00:05:02,887
What is it?

135
00:05:04,764 --> 00:05:06,557
I just got a visit
from Sean Cahill.

136
00:05:06,641 --> 00:05:07,684
About Gallo?

137
00:05:07,767 --> 00:05:09,227
I thought you said
he can't get him transferred.

138
00:05:09,310 --> 00:05:10,645
He can't. But it turns out

139
00:05:10,728 --> 00:05:12,063
there's a way
he can get you out.

140
00:05:12,146 --> 00:05:13,147
What do you mean "out"?

141
00:05:13,231 --> 00:05:16,317
I mean out, as in
you walk out that front door

142
00:05:16,401 --> 00:05:17,485
and you never look back.

143
00:05:18,945 --> 00:05:20,113
What's the catch?
Mike.

144
00:05:20,196 --> 00:05:21,322
Harvey, you're not here
telling me

145
00:05:21,406 --> 00:05:22,991
that I can get out
with that look on your face

146
00:05:23,074 --> 00:05:24,117
if there isn't
something else.

147
00:05:24,200 --> 00:05:25,785
He needs you to inform
on your cellmate.

148
00:05:25,868 --> 00:05:26,828
What?

149
00:05:26,911 --> 00:05:28,413
If whatever you get
leads to a conviction

150
00:05:28,496 --> 00:05:29,497
of his father-in-law,

151
00:05:29,580 --> 00:05:31,833
he'll commute your sentence
and you get to walk.

152
00:05:33,584 --> 00:05:34,585
What did the guy do?

153
00:05:34,669 --> 00:05:36,170
Who cares what he did?
I care.

154
00:05:36,254 --> 00:05:37,296
Because if it was so bad,

155
00:05:37,380 --> 00:05:38,548
why didn't Kevin turn on him
in the first place?

156
00:05:38,631 --> 00:05:40,800
Mike, what does it matter?
He can get you out.

157
00:05:40,883 --> 00:05:42,427
This is my
only friend in here.

158
00:05:42,510 --> 00:05:43,886
I'm not going to betray him.
Friend?

159
00:05:43,970 --> 00:05:45,096
Listen to me, God damn it.

160
00:05:45,179 --> 00:05:46,723
There's someone in here
trying to kill you

161
00:05:46,806 --> 00:05:48,016
and I'm giving you a way out.

162
00:05:48,099 --> 00:05:49,183
I'm taking care of Gallo.

163
00:05:49,267 --> 00:05:50,351
What the hell is that
supposed to mean?

164
00:05:50,435 --> 00:05:51,894
It means that I did
what you told me to do.

165
00:05:51,978 --> 00:05:53,730
I threatened to tell people
that he was an informant.

166
00:05:53,813 --> 00:05:55,189
But what I also did
was find out

167
00:05:55,273 --> 00:05:56,232
a way to get him parole.

168
00:05:56,315 --> 00:05:57,984
Parole? Are you crazy?

169
00:05:58,067 --> 00:05:59,360
He's not going
to get parole.

170
00:05:59,444 --> 00:06:00,570
Who's going
to say he deserves it?

171
00:06:00,653 --> 00:06:02,196
You know what, Harvey?
Instead of coming in here

172
00:06:02,280 --> 00:06:03,531
and telling me
to betray my cellmate

173
00:06:03,614 --> 00:06:04,824
because Gallo
will never get parole,

174
00:06:04,907 --> 00:06:06,284
maybe you should
be helping me
get it for him.

175
00:06:06,367 --> 00:06:08,703
I'm never helping that
piece of shit do anything.

176
00:06:08,786 --> 00:06:10,455
And this isn't about Gallo,
and you know it.

177
00:06:10,538 --> 00:06:12,457
No, it's about you telling me
to turn on the one guy

178
00:06:12,540 --> 00:06:14,709
in here that I trust based
on some plan that Cahill

179
00:06:14,792 --> 00:06:16,335
has that we don't even
know will work.

180
00:06:16,419 --> 00:06:17,462
No, Mike.

181
00:06:17,545 --> 00:06:19,464
It's about giving you
a chance to get your life back

182
00:06:19,547 --> 00:06:21,174
while it still
looks the same.

183
00:06:22,216 --> 00:06:24,218
Now, are you going
to take it or not?

